Cédric Beust ♔ wrote:

&gt;&gt;I think there&#39;s a lot of room for different ways of organizing tests.
&gt;&gt;For me, it&#39;s good for JUnit 4 to keep the one-class-instance-per-test
&gt;&gt;philosophy of JUnits 1 through 3. I find that if my code depends on too
&gt;&gt;much global state, or too many collaborators, I begin to feel it,
&gt;&gt;because it gets harder to test in JUnit. I find that if I ignore this
&gt;&gt;pain in the tests, eventually it becomes a pain in the code, so I like
&gt;&gt;JUnit&#39;s early warning.
&gt; 
&gt; 
&gt; I&#39;m not sure I see the connection between &quot;a new instance per method call&quot;
&gt; and &quot;parameters for test methods&quot;. How does one exclude the other?
&gt; 
&gt; With that in mind, I find that having the parameters on the constructor
&gt; 
&gt;&gt;reminds me of what&#39;s really going on.
&gt; 
&gt; 
&gt; 
&gt; Probably a personal thing, then.
&gt; 
&gt; I know I prefer:
&gt; 
&gt; // no constructor needed
&gt; public void validateXml(String xmlPath) { ... }
&gt; public void verifyApplicationIsDeployed(URL url) { ... }
&gt; 
&gt; over
&gt; 
&gt; public MyTest(String xmlPath, URL url) { ... }
&gt; public void validateXml() { ... }
&gt; public void verifyApplicationIsDeployed() { ... }
&gt; 
&gt; 
&gt; --
&gt; Cédric
